courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of the course, students should be able to:   
   
1. Demonstrate a systematic and up-to-date knowledge of the grammar of English, and a critical understanding of the nature of grammar and grammatical rules;   
2. Use an online English corpus (such as British National Corpus and Corpus of Contemporary American English) to search for data on any given grammatical structure or lexical expression;   
3. Critically analyze language data and use it as evidence to formulate appropriate generalizations to account for the grammatical patterns or structures in question, and to evaluate the validity of other explanations (including traditional prescriptive ‘rules’);   
4. Apply their knowledge of English grammar for pedagogical purposes, including the identification and explanation of learner errors.   
   
(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

Upon completion of this course, students are expected to be able to:   
1. explain the major theories of first and second language acquisition using academic terminology;    
2. analyse how individual and contextual factors contribute to English language development;   
3. design a thematic unit of work with a focus on differentiation;    
4. describe and justify the design of the unit of learning with Psycholinguistic theories in both written and spoken communication;   
5. identify the roles of language in society and in education;    
6. analyse the social aspects of language related to education in Hong Kong.   
   
(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

By the end of the course, participants will be able to:   
   
1. compare ways in which literature can be defined and used, and critically discuss different approaches and perspectives;   
2. develop a conceptual framework for understanding the uses and characteristics of the language in literature;   
3. apply concepts and techniques in analysing and talking about a broad range of literary texts;   
4. personalize and adapt approaches to literature in materials selection, task design and teaching strategies for integration into the language curriculum;   
5. foster interests in reading literature for personal and professional development.  
   
   
   
How the learning activities facilitate students to achieve the expected learning outcomes:  
   
   
The Course will take participants from the concepts of the language-literature interface through practical analyses to literary theories, drawing on their professional experience and language knowledge. It features multi-modal materials of different literary genres for students to try out the ideas and techniques derived from the conceptual framework and methodological component. Activities include discourse stylistic analysis, genre awareness practice, intensive reading, creative writing, materials development, task analysis, and curriculum tailoring and evaluation. Participants are expected to do the assigned readings, prepare for the tasks, and take an active part in class discussion and project presentation.  
   
   
(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

courses.course_syllabus:
The course will examine two to three contemporary issues in English Language teaching. The specific issues covered will be chosen with reference to current trends and innovations in English language education on the global level as well as recent developments in Hong Kong. For each contemporary issue to be covered, the following dimensions will be addressed:    
- Origin and underlying rationales;   
- Related pedagogical innovations to date;    
- Reflections on its relevance and/ or application in the Hong Kong context   
   
(For reference only, please refer to the course outline of respective teacher for details.)
